<div id="benandanti" class="thinker-section">
  <h2 class="section-head"><span class="section-num">01</span>The night battles</h2>
  <p>In the Friuli, in the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries, there were people called the <em>benandanti</em> — "those who go well," or "good walkers." On certain nights they believed they left their bodies and went out in spirit to fight: against witches, for the harvest. If they won, the fields were spared; if they lost, the year went hungry. They did not understand themselves as witches. They understood themselves as the village's protectors against witchcraft.</p>
  <p>Ginzburg reconstructed this world from the records of the people who came to destroy it. <em>The Night Battles</em> (1966) is built almost entirely from Inquisition trial transcripts — testimony given under questioning, by people who had no idea their words would survive them. He read those records not for what the inquisitors concluded but for what the accused kept insisting, against the leading questions, about what they did and why.</p>
</div>
<div id="reframing" class="thinker-section">
  <h2 class="section-head"><span class="section-num">02</span>How a knower becomes a witch</h2>
  <p>The drama of the transcripts is a slow collision. The benandanti arrived saying they fought witches. The Inquisition had a category for night-flight, spirit-battle, and ecstasy, and it was not "protector." It was "witch." Over decades of trials, the questions pressed in one direction, and the answers gradually bent to meet them. What had been a harvest tradition was reinterpreted, interrogation by interrogation, into the very thing it claimed to oppose.</p>
  <p>This is not a metaphor for enclosure. It is enclosure, caught on the page: a body of folk knowledge being overwritten by an institution with the power to define what it was. The benandanti did not change what they did. The frame around them changed, until the word for them became the word for their enemy.</p>
</div>
<div id="ecstasies" class="thinker-section">
  <h2 class="section-head"><span class="section-num">03</span>A substrate beneath the sabbath</h2>
  <p>Ginzburg's later work widened the case. <em>Ecstasies: Deciphering the Witches' Sabbath</em> (1989, English 1991) argues that beneath the European image of the witches' sabbath lies a far older substrate — fragments of shamanic cults, ecstatic journeys, spirit-battles for fertility, surfacing across Europe in forms the benandanti were only one local instance of. The sabbath the inquisitors described was not invented from nothing. It was assembled, in part, out of real practices the persecution did not understand and could not leave standing.</p>
</div>
<div id="enclosed-knower" class="thinker-section">
  <h2 class="section-head"><span class="section-num">04</span>The witch as the enclosed knower</h2>
  <p>This is where Ginzburg meets Federici, and the two halves of the same event lock together. Federici names what the witch hunts <em>did</em>: they removed the women who held communal knowledge, autonomous land, the skills that let villages feed and heal themselves without the wage. Enclosure of the body, of the common, of the knower. Ginzburg shows what was inside the thing being removed — not superstition, not hysteria, but a living folk cosmology with its own coherence, which the Inquisition did not merely punish but rewrote.</p>
  <div class="callout"><span class="callout-label">For the commons</span><p>The witch was the enclosed knower. Federici shows the enclosure; Ginzburg shows the knowing. Put together, the witch hunt stops being a panic that reason eventually cured and becomes what it was: the violent overwriting of a body of common knowledge by an institution with the power to rename it. The harvest-protector was reclassified as the thing she protected against — and the knowledge went into the fire under the name her persecutors had given it.</p></div>
</div>
<div id="lineage" class="thinker-section">
  <h2 class="section-head"><span class="section-num">05</span>A different inheritance</h2>
  <p>It is worth marking, beside the Eliade profile, what Ginzburg carried into this work. His father was Leone Ginzburg — philologist, historian, co-founder of the Einaudi publishing house, an anti-fascist who was murdered by the Gestapo in 1944. His mother was the novelist Natalia Ginzburg.</p>
  <p>The contrast with Eliade is exact. Eliade lent his prestige to a movement that made the nation holy and murdered in its name. Ginzburg came from a family that such a movement murdered for refusing it. The book draws on both — and does not pretend the difference between those two inheritances is small.</p>
</div>
